ask. вЂ‹You will give me the output of вЂ‹the prompt and tell me how well it solved the task. вЂ‹It's going to give us the task and you notice we're also, вЂ‹we're adding it, ask us questions, вЂ‹so it's going to give us the task. вЂ‹The task is going to be something that вЂ‹can be solved with a prompt, вЂ‹will write the prompt, вЂ‹and then it will run the prompt in вЂ‹order to generate the output that that prompt вЂ‹would have output and then вЂ‹it's going to tell us how good our prompt was. вЂ‹This is interesting. We're actually having вЂ‹it play a game where he's pretending вЂ‹to be prompted and then вЂ‹telling us how good our prompts are. вЂ‹Ask me questions until I tell you to stop. вЂ‹You will ask me a question, вЂ‹wait for my response, вЂ‹and then ask me another question вЂ‹after telling me how I did. вЂ‹Ask me the first question. вЂ‹It says, \\\"Great. вЂ‹Let's get started with this first task.\\\" вЂ‹Given a list of numbers, вЂ‹determine whether the list вЂ‹contains any duplicate elements. вЂ‹If it does return yes, there are duplicates. вЂ‹If it does not, no duplicate is found. вЂ‹Now we've got a specific prompt engineering task. вЂ‹We're going to have to figure out how do we вЂ‹write a prompt where we give it a list of вЂ‹numbers and have it return вЂ‹one or the other of these things and it's interesting. вЂ‹This is one of the challenges that вЂ‹we often face when we're dealing with вЂ‹a large language model is getting it вЂ‹to generate a precise output. вЂ‹It's giving us something where it has вЂ‹a thought component to it of like how do we design вЂ‹and tell it about what it is we're trying to achieve. вЂ‹But also, it's also got an output component. вЂ‹We're trying to match a specific output format. вЂ‹Then it says, \\\"Please write a prompt вЂ‹for me to solve this task.\\\" вЂ‹I'm going to solve this task using few shot examples. вЂ‹I give it a list of numbers, вЂ‹I show it some examples. вЂ‹I say basically in my prompt essay, вЂ‹here's the numbers 1, 2,